Introduction

Purpose of EDA

Explore the data set that we have been given and familiarize ourselves with some of the trends and patterns within the data. We have broken the EDA portion of this project into multiple sections, such as general insights, product insights, and demographic insights.

Exploring the data and becoming familiar with the data that we are working with will help us to build the best possible models with the most accuracy

Business Problem

Swire Coca-Cola is a large organization that produces, sells and distributes Coca-Cola and other beverages in 13 states across the American West.

While the demand for Swires core products is relatively know, they also introduce new and innovative products on a regular basis. These products are often limited time only products meant to drive demand. Swire Coca-Cola needs to accurately predict demand for their innovative products. Historical data from other projects can help but will not provide a fully accurate prediction as each product is different and will target different regions, demographics, etc. The purpose of the project is to use the available demographic and historical product data to accurately predict demand of future innovation products.

Analytics Problem

There are a few analytics problems that we will need to solve as part of this project.

First, we need to decided what to do with the data currently outside of the main market demand data frame. We have demographic data and zip code data in separate data frames and we will likely need to utilize this to accurately forecast demand in certain regions or for certain demographics. For the questions related specifically to certain regions, we will need to incorporate that data to make accurate predictions.

Second, we have historical data but the historical data we have includes products released for varying time frames. Equally, our products that we need to forecast for also have varying time frames, such as 13 weeks, 6 months, etc. We will try and use the historical data for the time periods that match to answer those questions

Success Metrics

Success will be determined by our ability to provide accurate forecasts that allow Swire to accurately provide supply to meet demand, without leaving leftover products in supply while also not leaving any demand unserved. Our success will be determined by the financial impact that our predictions will have on the companys profit, which we will calculate using our model and some industry standard metrics.

Description of the Data

We have 3 data sets that are available to build our model, and each will be crucial in leveraging when building our models.

The first data set is the Market Demand which includes historical data of past products. These products include various categories, brands, caloric segments, and packaging. We have over 24 million rows of this data, so we need to factor in the size of the data and how we will account for this.

The second data set is a demographics sheet. This includes various demographic information such as age, income, gender, household income, and segment. We can utilize this to forecast sales in areas that have similar demographics.

Lastly, we have zip code information that will allow us to map the historical sales data to specific zip codes.

Discussion of Missing Data

There were some NAs which were imputed by Jake and as a team we are now using a data set that does not include missing data

Summary and Results

There are a lot of things that we can take away from these general summaries of the market demand datasheet.

When analyzing the DATE column, we see roughly 3 years worth of data available. Some of the products in the data set have a DURATION of the full 3 years, while others are less than 6 months. Those that are less than 6 months will likely be the most relevant to our innovation product predictions.

When analyzing the data, the DATE attribute will be very important and it could be useful to make subsets of our models with the data for products with different date ranges, such as 13 weeks, less than 6 months, etc to try and use data that is most similar to the questions we are trying to answer

We see that CATEGORY while Energy Drinks are the type of drinks that they make the most money off per unit as the price is nearly twice as high as the other Categories, SSD is by far the dominant category that they sell.

Swire-CC appears to be middle of the road in terms of the other Manfacturers in the data set when it comes to total sales in dollars and total unit sales. However, their low price per unit in comparison to other manufacturers is concerning. They are having to sell more total units to reach the same number of total dollars than other manufacturers would, which means they will incure more costs and have less profit for the same amount of total dollars sold. When doing our analysis, we will want to see if we can focus on items that have a higher average unit price

The two different caloric segments (diet/lite vs regular) sell for roughly the same amount per unit, but they do a lot more sales both in units and total dollars of regular drinks. This indicates a higher demand for regular over diet soda.

Overall, there are so many observations of the data that our main task will be deciding what fields to focus on and what questions to answer. Once we do that, we will be able to use the large amounts of observations to have sufficient data to field into the models that we build.
